The U.S. and Germany issued a Joint Statement on Support for Ukraine, European Energy Security, and our Climate Goals in July 2021, outlining measures to address Ukraine’s concerns over Nord Stream 2. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_5.4"]  
The statement did not make the pipeline’s completion explicitly contingent on Ukraine’s consent but committed to mitigating Russia’s potential coercive use of energy. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_5.4"]  
Germany pledged to take national action and press for EU-level measures, including sanctions, if Russia used energy as a weapon against Ukraine. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_1.3","msmarco_v2.1_doc_5.4"]  
Both countries expressed readiness to impose new sanctions on Russian energy exports under such circumstances. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_1.3"]  
They also committed to safeguard and increase reverse gas-flow capacity to Ukraine to protect it from future supply cuts. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_5.4"]  
Germany agreed to leverage all available means to extend Ukraine’s gas-transit deal with Russia by up to ten years beyond 2024 and to appoint a special envoy for these negotiations. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_5.4","msmarco_v2.1_doc_3.2"]  
A U.S.–German Climate and Energy Partnership was established to support Ukraine’s decarbonization via a Green Fund, with at least $175 million from Germany and a goal of mobilizing $1 billion. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_5.3","msmarco_v2.1_doc_6.1"]  
Analysts and Ukrainian officials, however, criticized the agreement’s commitments as non-binding and lacking concrete implementation mechanisms and security guarantees. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_1.3","msmarco_v2.1_doc_4.1"]